{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Diadenylate cyclase catalyses the condensation of 2 ATP molecules into cyclic di-AMP (c-di-AMP), a signaling compound secreted into the host's cytosol by bacterial pathogens, such as Listeria monocytogenes. This compound triggers the cytosolic surveillance pathway (CSP), a host pathway of innate immunity [[cite:PUB00070986]]. Apart from a role in the establishment of bacterial infection, c-di-AMP seems to be involved in coordinating bacterial growth, cell wall stability, and responses to stress [[cite:PUB00078859]].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This entry includes CdaA and CdaS from Bacillus subtilis [[cite:PUB00079210]]. CdaA produces the c-di-AMP that is required for cell wall homeostasis [[cite:PUB00078858]]. CdaS contains an N-terminal domain that consists of two Î±-helices and a C-terminal catalytically active diadenylate cyclase (DAC) domain. The cyclic di-AMP formed by CdaS is required for efficient germination  [[cite:PUB00079209]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "2fb5", "name" "Structural Genomics; The crystal structure of the hypothetical membrane spanning protein from Bacillus cereus"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036888", "name" "DNA integrity scanning protein, DisA, N-terminal domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"pirsf" {"PIRSF004793" "Uncharacterised conserved protein, UCP004793 type"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Diadenylate cyclase", "short" "C-di-AMP_synthase"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 3, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 3173, "taxa" 13161, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 15085, "sets" 0, "proteins" 15073, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 11307}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZYME is a repository of information relative to the nomenclature of 